# How Linux starts & stays running

Two questions, one answer вҖ” a chain ending at **systemd, PID 1**.

```
power в”Җв–¶ BIOS/UEFI в”Җв–¶ GRUB в”Җв–¶ kernel + initramfs в”Җв–¶ systemd (PID 1)
                                                       в”Ӯ
                  в”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Ө
               services    targets    journal    packages
              (.service)  (runlevels) (journald)  (apt/dnf)
```

The **boot chain** hands control down: firmware finds a disk вҶ’ **GRUB** loads the kernel вҶ’ **initramfs** mounts real `/` вҶ’ **systemd** runs as first process. From there, systemd runs *everything*.

## systemd manages the system as units

- **`.service`** вҖ” daemons. Drive with **`systemctl`**, read logs with **`journalctl`**
- **`.target`** вҖ” runlevels (server vs desktop)
- **`.timer`** вҖ” the modern cron

**This module:** systemd & units вҶ’ `systemctl` вҶ’ writing a service вҶ’ targets вҶ’ logs вҶ’ the boot chain in detail вҶ’ **packages** & **repos**.
